The spread (difference) between the average yields of southern and northern state bonds is another measure of market beliefs about war risk.
War would, and did, increase the risk of southern bonds relative to northern bonds.%
\footnote{
  The spread between southern and northern bonds can be approximately interpreted as the difference in default risk, where default is complete. 
  This interpretation is based off the same approximation as equation \ref{eq:4}.
}
This was observed after Fort Sumter, in which the yields of southern states increased 3--8 percentage points, while the yields of northern states increased only 0.01 to 0.35 percentage points (Table \ref{tab:sumter}).
Since war would have a differential effect on the risk of northern and southern state bonds, as war risk increases, the spread between southern and northern state bonds should increase.
The most immediate differential effect of the war on southern state bond holders in the north was that the states stopped paying interest payments \parencites[974]{BankersMagazine1861}[159,479]{BankersMagazine1862}.%
\footnote{It seems that after the war, southern states repaid debt issued \textit{before} the war in some manner; though all defaulted on any debts issued while part of the Confederacy, and some defaulted on debt issued by reconstruction governments after the war. }
Using this spread rather than raw yields has the advantage of controlling for factors which have the same influence on all state bonds.
For example, as noted below, yields spiked during the Panic of 1857, but the spread between southern and northern bonds did not spike.
There may still be fundamental differences between the risks of northern and southern states due to many reasons, but focusing on changes in the spread controls for any of these factors which are constant over the time period considered.
It is likely that war risk would be the most influential factor influencing the spread.

The data used to calculate the spread consists of the yields of northern (Indiana, Ohio and Pennsylvania) and southern (Georgia, Louisiana, North Carolina, Tennessee and Virginia) bonds for the full period.%
\footnote{The border states of Kentucky and Missouri are not included in these calculations.}
The model used to estimate spread is described in section \ref{sec:model-south-north-yield-spreads}.
